I am experiencing the same issue with `DateField`. I need to focus the actual "input" (which is actually the first of multiple inputs in a group) and it seems to require quite a bit of work to attach the ref to the right place regardless of the user's locale.

The refs passed directly to `DateField` and `DateInput` are applied to the outer elements, which aren't the focusable ones. What _does_ work is passing the ref to the first `DateSegment`. However, there are no values in the FaC of `DateInput` that allow me to figure out which segment is the first one. An easy way to do it is as follows:

```tsx
function MyCustomDateField() {
  const ref = React.useRef(null);

  return (
    <DateField>
      <Label>Label</Label>
      <DateInput>
        {(segment) => <DateSegment segment={segment} ref={segment.type === 'month' ? ref : undefined} />}
      </DateInput>
    </DateField>
  );
}
```

but of course this is making an assumption about the user's locale and is inflexible. Probably I can use the internationalization library to determine which is the type of the first segment, but that would be a lot of work for this simple functionality.

Something that would help would be if the FaC included a value that indicated if the segment being rendered is the first editable segment of the input. A simple index passed in could work, though I'm not sure if there are any cases where the first segment is actually a literal (which cannot be focused - we need the first _editable_ segment).

For instance:

```tsx
<DateInput>
  {(segment, index) => <DateSegment segment={segment} ref={index === 0 ? ref : undefined} />}
</DateInput>
```

But ideally there would just be one simple place to attach the ref as it is for other non-compound form inputs.

@wmodden @joestrkr I've found a solution that doesn't require _too_ much extra code and seems to work for me for now. Basically, we make use of the `DateFieldStateContext` to find out which segment is the first editable segment, and then we can use that information to pass the ref to only that segment.

The code looks something like this:

```ts
const MyCustomDateInput = React.forwardRef<HTMLInputElement>(function DateInput(_props, ref) {
  const { segments } = useContext(DateFieldStateContext)!;
  // Find the first editable date segment - this is the one we want to focus
  // when focusing the input
  const firstSegmentType = segments.find(
  	({ isEditable }) => isEditable,
  )?.type;

  return (
    <DateInput>
      {(segment) => (
        <DateSegment segment={segment} ref={segment.type === firstSegmentType ? ref : undefined} />
      )}
    </DateInput>
  );
});

function MyCustomDateField() {
  const ref = React.useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);

  return (
    <DateField>
      <Label>Label</Label>
      <MyCustomDateInput ref={ref} />
    </DateField>
  );
}
```

`MyCustomDateField` would then be updated to use a forwarded ref.

